# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] In statistics, an **autoregressive** (**AR**) **model** is a modelled representation of a type of random process.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] It can be used to describe time-varying processes from many natural and artificial sources.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] The model specifies output variables that are dependent linearly on their own previous values on a stochastic basis.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] The model is in the form of a stochastic difference equation (or recurrence relation) which should not be confused with a differential equation.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] Another important extension is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, where the autoregressive coefficients are allowed to change over time to model evolving or non-stationary processes.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] TVAR models are widely applied in cases where the underlying dynamics of the system are not constant, such as in sensors time series modelling, climate science, economics and finance (as econometrics), signal processing, telecommunications, radar systems, and biological signals.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] Unlike the moving-average (MA) model, the autoregressive model is not always stationary; non-stationarity can arise either due to the presence of a unit root or due to time-varying model parameters, as in time-varying autoregressive models.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] Large language models are called autoregressive, but they are not a classical autoregressive model in this sense because they are not linear.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] The notation $AR(p)$ indicates an autoregressive model of order *p*.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] where $\varphi _{1},\ldots ,\varphi _{p}$ are the *parameters* of the model, and $\varepsilon _{t}$ is white noise.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] An autoregressive model can thus be viewed as the output of an all-pole infinite impulse response filter whose input is white noise.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] Some parameter constraints are necessary for the model to remain weak-sense stationary.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] For example, processes in the AR(1) model with $|\varphi _{1}|\geq 1$ are not stationary.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] More generally, for an AR(*p*) model to be weak-sense stationary, the roots of the polynomial $\Phi (z):=\textstyle 1-\sum _{i=1}^{p}\varphi _{i}z^{i}$ must lie outside the unit circle, i.e., each (complex) root $z_{i}$ must satisfy $|z_{i}|>1$ (see pages 89,92 ).
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] In an AR process, a one-time shock affects values of the evolving variable infinitely far into the future.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] A non-zero value for $\varepsilon _{t}$ at say time *t*=1 affects $X_{1}$ by the amount $\varepsilon _{1}$ .
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] Then by the AR equation for $X_{2}$ in terms of $X_{1}$ , this affects $X_{2}$ by the amount $\varphi _{1}\varepsilon _{1}$ .
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] Then by the AR equation for $X_{3}$ in terms of $X_{2}$ , this affects $X_{3}$ by the amount $\varphi _{1}^{2}\varepsilon _{1}$ .
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] Continuing this process shows that the effect of $\varepsilon _{1}$ never ends, although if the process is stationary then the effect diminishes toward zero in the limit.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] Because each shock affects *X* values infinitely far into the future from when they occur, any given value *X**t* is affected by shocks occurring infinitely far into the past.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] When the polynomial division on the right side is carried out, the polynomial in the backshift operator applied to $\varepsilon _{t}$ has an infinite order—that is, an infinite number of lagged values of $\varepsilon _{t}$ appear on the right side of the equation.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] where *B* is the backshift operator, where $\varphi (\cdot )$ is the function defining the autoregression, and where $\varphi _{k}$ are the coefficients in the autoregression.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] The formula is valid only if all the roots have multiplicity 1.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] The autocorrelation function of an AR(*p*) process is a sum of decaying exponentials.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] The simplest AR process is AR(0), which has no dependence between the terms.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] Only the error/innovation/noise term contributes to the output of the process, so in the figure, AR(0) corresponds to white noise.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] For an AR(1) process with a positive $\varphi$ , only the previous term in the process and the noise term contribute to the output.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] If $\varphi$ is close to 0, then the process still looks like white noise, but as $\varphi$ approaches 1, the output gets a larger contribution from the previous term relative to the noise.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] This results in a "smoothing" or integration of the output, similar to a low pass filter.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] For an AR(2) process, the previous two terms and the noise term contribute to the output.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] If both $\varphi _{1}$ and $\varphi _{2}$ are positive, the output will resemble a low pass filter, with the high frequency part of the noise decreased.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] If $\varphi _{1}$ is positive while $\varphi _{2}$ is negative, then the process favors changes in sign between terms of the process.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] This can be linked to edge detection or detection of change in direction.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] An AR(1) process is given by: $X_{t}=\varphi X_{t-1}+\varepsilon _{t}\,$ where $\varepsilon _{t}$ is a white noise process with zero mean and constant variance $\sigma _{\varepsilon }^{2}$ .
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] (Note: The subscript on $\varphi _{1}$ has been dropped.) The process is weak-sense stationary if $|\varphi |<1$ since it is obtained as the output of a stable filter whose input is white noise.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] where $\sigma _{\varepsilon }$ is the standard deviation of $\varepsilon _{t}$ .
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] and then by noticing that the quantity above is a stable fixed point of this relation.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] It can be seen that the autocovariance function decays with a decay time (also called time constant) of $\tau =1/(1-\varphi )$ .
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] The spectral density function is the Fourier transform of the autocovariance function.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] This expression is periodic due to the discrete nature of the $X_{j}$ , which is manifested as the cosine term in the denominator.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] where $\gamma =1/\tau$ is the angular frequency associated with the decay time $\tau$ .
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] An alternative expression for $X_{t}$ can be derived by first substituting $\varphi X_{t-2}+\varepsilon _{t-1}$ for $X_{t-1}$ in the defining equation.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] It is seen that $X_{t}$ is white noise convolved with the $\varphi ^{k}$ kernel plus the constant mean.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] If the white noise $\varepsilon _{t}$ is a Gaussian process then $X_{t}$ is also a Gaussian process.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] In other cases, the central limit theorem indicates that $X_{t}$ will be approximately normally distributed when $\varphi$ is close to one.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] For $\varepsilon _{t}=0$ , the process $X_{t}=\varphi X_{t-1}$ will be a geometric progression (*exponential* growth or decay).
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] In this case, the solution can be found analytically: $X_{t}=a\varphi ^{t}$ whereby a is an unknown constant (initial condition).
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] The AR(1) model is the discrete-time analogy of the continuous Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] It is therefore sometimes useful to understand the properties of the AR(1) model cast in an equivalent form.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] The partial autocorrelation of an AR(p) process equals zero at lags larger than *p*, so the appropriate maximum lag *p* is the one after which the partial autocorrelations are all zero.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] There are many ways to estimate the coefficients, such as the ordinary least squares procedure or method of moments (through Yule–Walker equations).
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] It is based on parameters $\varphi _{i}$ where *i* = 1, ..., *p*.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] There is a direct correspondence between these parameters and the covariance function of the process, and this correspondence can be inverted to determine the parameters from the autocorrelation function (which is itself obtained from the covariances).
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] This is done using the Yule–Walker equations.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] The Yule–Walker equations, named for Udny Yule and Gilbert Walker, are the following set of equations.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] Here $\gamma _{m}$ is the autocovariance function of Xt, $\sigma _{\varepsilon }$ is the standard deviation of the input noise process, and $\delta _{m,0}$ is the Kronecker delta function.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] An alternative formulation is in terms of the autocorrelation function.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] The AR parameters are determined by the first *p*+1 elements $\rho (\tau )$ of the autocorrelation function.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] The above equations (the Yule–Walker equations) provide several routes to estimating the parameters of an AR(*p*) model, by replacing the theoretical covariances with estimated values.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] but the reasoning behind this applies to the use of any set of estimated AR parameters.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] Compared to the estimation scheme using only the forward prediction equations, different estimates of the autocovariances are produced, and the estimates have different stability properties.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] Other possible approaches to estimation include maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] Substantial differences in the results of these approaches can occur if the observed series is short, or if the process is close to non-stationarity.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] The terms involving square roots are all real in the case of complex poles since they exist only when $\varphi _{2}<0$ .
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] The process is non-stationary when the poles are on or outside the unit circle, or equivalently when the characteristic roots are on or inside the unit circle.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] The process is stable when the poles are strictly within the unit circle (roots strictly outside the unit circle), or equivalently when the coefficients are in the triangle $-1\leq \varphi _{2}\leq 1-|\varphi _{1}|$ .
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] The impulse response of a system is the change in an evolving variable in response to a change in the value of a shock term *k* periods earlier, as a function of *k*.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] Since the AR model is a special case of the vector autoregressive model, the computation of the impulse response in vector autoregression#impulse response applies here.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] have been estimated, the autoregression can be used to forecast an arbitrary number of periods into the future.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] The output of the autoregressive equation is the forecast for the first unobserved period.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] Then for future periods the same procedure is used, each time using one more forecast value on the right side of the predictive equation until, after *p* predictions, all *p* right-side values are predicted values from preceding steps.
[src:gpt-architecture/autoregressive-model] Each of the last three can be quantified and combined to give a confidence interval for the *n*-step-ahead predictions; the confidence interval will become wider as *n* increases because of the use of an increasing number of estimated values for the right-side variables.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] A **generative pre-trained transformer** (**GPT**) is a type of large language model (LLM) that is widely used in generative artificial intelligence chatbots.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] GPTs are based on a deep learning architecture called the transformer.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] They are pre-trained on large datasets of unlabeled content, and able to generate novel content.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] OpenAI was the first to apply generative pre-training to the transformer architecture, introducing the GPT-1 model in 2018.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The company has since released many bigger GPT models.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The chatbot ChatGPT, released in late 2022 (using GPT-3.5), was followed by many competitor chatbots using their own generative pre-trained transformers to generate text, such as Gemini, DeepSeek and Claude.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] GPTs are primarily used to generate text, but can be trained to generate other kinds of data.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] For example, GPT-4o can process and generate text, images and audio.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] To improve performance on complex tasks, some GPTs, such as OpenAI o3, allocate more computation time analyzing the problem before generating an output, and are called reasoning models.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] In 2025, GPT-5 was released with a router that automatically selects whether to use a faster model or slower reasoning model based on the provided task.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] During the 2010s, improved machine learning algorithms, more powerful computers, and an increase in the amount of digitized material allowed for an AI boom.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Separately, the concept of generative pre-training (GP) was a long-established technique in machine learning.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] GP is a form of self-supervised learning wherein a model is first trained on a large, unlabeled dataset (the "pre-training" step) to learn to generate data points.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] This pre-trained model is then adapted to a specific task using a labeled dataset (the "fine-tuning" step).
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The transformer architecture for deep learning is the core technology of a GPT.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Developed by researchers at Google, it was introduced in the paper "Attention Is All You Need", which was released in 2017.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The transformer architecture solved many of the performance issues that were associated with older recurrent neural network (RNN) designs for natural language processing (NLP).
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The architecture's use of an attention mechanism allows models to process entire sequences of text at once, enabling the training of much larger and more sophisticated models.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Since 2017, available transformer-based NLP systems have been capable of processing, mining, organizing, connecting, contrasting, and summarizing texts as well as answering questions from textual input.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] On June 11, 2018, OpenAI researchers and engineers published a paper called "Improving Language Understanding by Generative Pre-Training", which introduced GPT-1, the first GPT model.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] It was designed as a transformer-based large language model that used generative pre-training (GP) on BookCorpus, a diverse text corpus, followed by discriminative fine-tuning to focus on specific language tasks.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] This semi-supervised approach was seen as a breakthrough.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] GPT models use only the decoder part of the transformer architecture, pre-trained to predict the next token in a sequence.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Previously, the best-performing neural models in natural language processing (NLP) had commonly employed supervised learning from large amounts of manually labeled data – training a large language model with this approach would have been prohibitively expensive and time-consuming.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] On February 14, 2019, OpenAI introduced GPT-2, a larger model that could generate coherent text.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Created as a direct scale-up of its predecessor, it had both its parameter count and dataset size increased by a factor of 10.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] GPT-2 has 1.5 billion parameters and was trained on WebText, a 40-gigabyte dataset of 8 million web pages.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Citing risks of malicious use, OpenAI opted for a "staged release", initially publishing smaller versions of the model before releasing the full 1.5-billion-parameter model in November.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] On May 28, 2020, OpenAI introduced GPT-3, a model with 175 billion parameters that was trained on a larger dataset compared to GPT-2.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] It marked a significant advancement in few-shot and zero-shot learning abilities.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] With few examples, it could perform various tasks that it was not explicitly trained for.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Following the release of GPT-3, OpenAI started using reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) to align models' behavior more closely with human preferences.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] This led to the development of InstructGPT, a fine-tuned version of GPT-3.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] OpenAI further refined InstructGPT to create ChatGPT, the flagship chatbot product of OpenAI that was launched on November 30, 2022.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] ChatGPT was initially based on GPT-3.5, but it was later transitioned to the GPT-4 model, which was released on March 14, 2023.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] GPT-4 was also integrated into parts of several applications, including Microsoft Copilot, GitHub Copilot, Snapchat, Khan Academy, and Duolingo.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The immense popularity of ChatGPT spurred widespread development of competing GPT-based systems from other organizations.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] EleutherAI released a series of open-weight models, including GPT-J in 2021.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Other major technology companies later developed their own GPT models, such as Google's PaLM and Gemini as well as Meta AI's Llama.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Many subsequent GPT models have been trained to be multimodal (able to process or to generate multiple types of data).
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] For example, GPT-4o can both process and generate text, images, and audio.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Additionally, GPT models like o3 and DeepSeek R1 have been trained with reinforcement learning to generate multi-step chain-of-thought reasoning before producing a final answer, which helps to solve complex problems in domains such as mathematics.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] On August 7, 2025, OpenAI released GPT-5, which includes a router that automatically selects whether to use a faster model or slower reasoning model based on task.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] A foundation model is an AI model trained on broad data at scale such that it can be adapted to a wide range of downstream tasks.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The most recent OpenAI's *GPT-n* series model is GPT-5.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Meta AI (formerly Facebook) also has a generative transformer-based foundational large language model, known as LLaMA.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Foundational GPTs can also employ modalities other than text, for input and/or output.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] GPT-4 is a multi-modal LLM that is capable of processing text and image input (though its output is limited to text).
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Regarding multimodal *output*, some generative transformer-based models are used for text-to-image technologies such as diffusion and parallel decoding.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Such kinds of models can serve as visual foundation models (VFMs) for developing downstream systems that can work with images.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The computational and memory requirements of transformer-based models increase significantly as they scale to larger sizes and longer input sequences.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The standard self-attention mechanism has a quadratic complexity with respect to input sequence length, as described in *Attention Is All You Need*.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Researchers proposed a number of efficiency improvements like sparse attention mechanisms and memory-efficient architectures that reduce computational costs while supporting longer context windows.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Models like BigBird, Reformer, and FlashAttention demonstrate structured attention patterns or optimized computation to improve scalability and efficiency.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] This has helped large language models to efficiently process long input sequences with reduced memory and computation during both training and inference.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Scaling laws describe empirical relationships between the performance of large language models and factors such as model size, dataset size, and computational resources.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Empirical work has found that performance tends to follow approximate power-law relationships as these factors increase.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Larger models trained on more data generally achieve lower training loss and better generalization.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Later work suggests that performance is not determined by parameter count alone, but by how model size, data, and compute are balanced during training.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] These observations have influenced the development of successive GPT models, particularly in decisions about architecture design, dataset composition, and training strategies.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Emergent abilities refer to capabilities that appear in large language models only when they reach a certain scale and are not present in smaller versions of the same models.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] These abilities are considered "emergent" because they arise as model size, training data, and compute increase.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Examples of emergent abilities include multi-step reasoning, in-context learning (the ability to perform tasks based on examples provided in prompts without additional training), and improved performance on complex language and reasoning benchmarks.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Research suggests that these capabilities do not scale linearly, but instead appear once models exceed certain thresholds in size and training scale.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] This phenomenon has influenced the development of larger GPT models and contributed to their increased effectiveness across a wide range of tasks.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] OpenAI, which created the first generative pre-trained transformer (GPT) in 2018, asserted in 2023 that "GPT" should be regarded as a *brand* of OpenAI.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] In April 2023, OpenAI revised the brand guidelines in its terms of service to indicate that other businesses using its API to run their AI services would no longer be able to include "GPT" in such names or branding.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] In May 2023, OpenAI engaged a brand management service to notify its API customers of this policy, although these notifications stopped short of making overt legal claims (such as allegations of trademark infringement or demands to cease and desist).
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] As of November 2023, OpenAI still prohibits its API licensees from naming their own products with "GPT", but it has begun enabling its ChatGPT Plus subscribers to make "custom versions of ChatGPT" called GPTs on the OpenAI site.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] OpenAI's terms of service says that its subscribers may use "GPT" in the names of these, although it's "discouraged".
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Relatedly, OpenAI has applied to the United States Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO) to seek domestic trademark registration for the term "GPT" in the field of AI.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] OpenAI sought to expedite handling of its application, but the USPTO declined that request in April 2023.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] In May 2023, the USPTO responded to the application with a determination that "GPT" was both descriptive and generic.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] As of November 2023, OpenAI continued to pursue its argument.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] For any given type or scope of trademark protection in the U.S., OpenAI would need to establish that the term is actually "distinctive" to their specific offerings in addition to being a broader technical term for the kind of technology.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Some media reports suggested in 2023 that OpenAI may be able to obtain trademark registration based indirectly on the fame of its GPT-based chatbot product, ChatGPT, for which OpenAI has *separately* sought protection (and which it has sought to enforce more strongly).
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Other reports have indicated that registration for the bare term "GPT" seems unlikely to be granted, as it is used frequently as a common term to refer simply to AI systems that involve generative pre-trained transformers.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] In any event, to whatever extent exclusive rights in the term may occur the U.S., others would need to avoid using it for similar products or services in ways likely to cause confusion.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] If such rights ever became broad enough to implicate other well-established uses in the field, the trademark doctrine of *descriptive fair use* could still continue non-brand-related usage.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] In the European Union, the European Union Intellectual Property Office registered "GPT" as a trade mark of OpenAI in spring 2023.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] However, since spring 2024 the registration is being challenged and is pending cancellation.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] In Switzerland, the Swiss Federal Institute of Intellectual Property registered "GPT" as a trade mark of OpenAI in spring 2023.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] The evaluation of generative pre-trained transformer models is carried out using a range of benchmarks and metrics, which aim to assess their performance across different tasks.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Common approaches include accuracy on standard datasets, as well as other features such as robustness, bias, and toxicity.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] These models are typically tested on tasks such as natural language understanding, reasoning, answering queries, and code generation.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Sometimes they combine multiple tasks to provide a broader assessment of model performance across domains.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] More recent approaches extend these evaluations to include other features such as fairness, efficiency, and transparency, in order to get a more accurate assessment of these models.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Evaluation remains an active area of research, as existing tests may not accurately reflect real-world performance or the risks associated with large-scale generative models.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Generative pre-trained transformer models have raised a range of ethical and societal concerns, particularly regarding bias, misinformation, and environmental impact.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Large language models can reproduce and amplify patterns present in their training data, including social biases, which may lead to unfair or misleading outputs.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] These models have also been associated with generating inaccurate or misleading information as they are designed to produce fluent text rather than to verify factual accuracy.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] This has an impact on their use in applications such as automated content generation and information dissemination.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Training large-scale models also requires huge computational resources, contributing to increased energy consumption and environmental costs.
[src:gpt-architecture/generative-pre-trained-transformer] Concerns about the environmental impact of large AI systems have led to calls for more efficient training methods and more transparency in reporting resource usage.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] GPT-2 was created as a "direct scale-up" of GPT-1 with a ten-fold increase in both its parameter count and the size of its training dataset.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] It was superseded by the GPT-3 and GPT-4 models, which are no longer open source.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] GPT-2 has, like its predecessor GPT-1 and its successors GPT-3, GPT-4 and GPT-5, a generative pre-trained transformer architecture, implementing a deep neural network, specifically a transformer model, which uses attention instead of older recurrence- and convolution-based architectures.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] Attention mechanisms allow the model to selectively focus on segments of input text it predicts to be the most relevant.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] This model allows for greatly increased parallelization, and outperforms previous benchmarks for RNN/CNN/LSTM-based models.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] Since the transformer architecture enabled massive parallelization, GPT models could be trained on larger corpora than previous NLP (natural language processing) models.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] While the GPT-1 model demonstrated that the approach was viable, GPT-2 would further explore the emergent properties of networks trained on extremely large corpora.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] *CommonCrawl*, a large corpus produced by web crawling and previously used in training NLP systems, was considered due to its large size, but was rejected after further review revealed large amounts of unintelligible content.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] Instead, OpenAI developed a new corpus, known as *WebText*; rather than scraping content indiscriminately from the World Wide Web, WebText was generated by scraping only pages linked to by Reddit posts that had received at least 3 karma prior to December 2017.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] The corpus was subsequently cleaned; HTML documents were parsed into plain text, duplicate pages were eliminated, and Wikipedia pages were removed (since their presence in many other datasets could have induced overfitting).
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] Documentation surrounding the cost of training GPT-2 is limited.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] According to a recent statement by Andrej Karpathy, GPT-2 was trained by OpenAI on 32 TPU v3 chips for 168 hours (7 days), at approximately $8 per TPU v3 per hour, for a total estimated compute cost of about $43,000.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] Other sources have cited a training cost of approximately $256 per hour.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] Comparable large language models using transformer architectures have had their costs documented in more detail; the training processes for BERT and XLNet consumed, respectively, $6,912 and $245,000 of resources.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] GPT-2 was first announced on 14 February 2019.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] The GPT-2 series contained 4 models, reported in the paper.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] They were not released all at once, but in stages.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] One commonly-cited justification was that, since generated text was usually completely novel, it could be used by spammers to evade automated filters; OpenAI demonstrated a version of GPT-2 fine-tuned to "generate infinite positive – or negative – reviews of products".
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] Another justification was that GPT-2 could be used to generate text that was obscene or racist.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] Researchers such as Jeremy Howard warned of "the technology to totally fill Twitter, email, and the web up with reasonable-sounding, context-appropriate prose, which would drown out all other speech and be impossible to filter".
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] The Allen Institute for Artificial Intelligence, in response to GPT-2, announced a tool to detect "neural fake news".
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] The cloud compute costs for OpenGPT-2 were given as approximately $50,000.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] On August 20, 2019, OpenAI released a partial version of GPT-2, with 774 million parameters (roughly half the size of the full 1.5 billion parameter model).
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] Two other smaller releases of GPT-2 are available, including the small version of 124M parameters and the medium size of 355M parameters.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] Both are available to download from Huggingface.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] GPT-2 deployment is resource-intensive; the full version of the model is larger than five gigabytes, making it difficult to embed locally into applications, and consumes large amounts of RAM.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] In addition, performing a single prediction "can occupy a CPU at 100% utilization for several minutes", and even with GPU processing, "a single prediction can take seconds".
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] To alleviate these issues, the company Hugging Face created **DistilGPT2**, using knowledge distillation to produce a smaller model that "scores a few points lower on some quality benchmarks", but is "33% smaller and twice as fast".
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] Even before the release of the full version, GPT-2 was used for a variety of applications and services, as well as for entertainment.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] In 2019, AI Dungeon was launched, which used GPT-2 to generate dynamic text adventures based on user input.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] AI Dungeon now offers access to the largest release of GPT-3 API as an optional paid upgrade, the free version of the site uses the 2nd largest release of GPT-3.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] Latitude, the company formed around AI Dungeon, raised $3.3 million in seed funding in 2021.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] Several websites host interactive demonstrations of different instances of GPT-2 and other transformer models.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] A study by the University of Amsterdam employing a modified Turing test found that at least in some scenarios, participants were unable to distinguish poems generated by GPT-2 from those written by humans.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] Researchers have also examined GPT-2's capacity for prose through fine-tuning on individual authors.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] Elkins and Chun (2020) reported that fine-tuned GPT-2 could imitate aspects of authorial style in short passages, though it remained prone to verbatim reproduction of training material.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] (2022) similarly found that GPT-2 fine-tuned on the poetry of individual Romantic-era authors could learn stylistic patterns, but that overfitting led to frequent replication or reordering of source text rather than original composition.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] On May 9, 2023, OpenAI released a mapped version of GPT-2.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] OpenAI used successor model, GPT-4, to map each neuron of GPT-2 to determine their functions.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] One example of generalized learning is GPT-2's ability to perform machine translation between French and English, for which task GPT-2's performance was assessed using WMT-14 translation tasks.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] Despite this, GPT-2 achieved 5 BLEU on the WMT-14 English-to-French test set (slightly below the score of a translation via word-for-word substitution).
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] It was also able to outperform several contemporary (2017) unsupervised machine translation baselines on the French-to-English test set, where GPT-2 achieved 11.5 BLEU.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] This remained below the highest-performing contemporary unsupervised approach (2019), which had achieved 33.5 BLEU.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] However, other models used large amounts of French text to achieve these results; GPT-2 was estimated to have used a monolingual French corpus approximately 1/500 the size of comparable approaches.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] GPT-2 was to be followed by the 175-billion-parameter GPT-3, revealed to the public in 2020 (whose source code has never been made available).
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-2] Access to GPT-3 is provided exclusively through APIs offered by OpenAI and Microsoft.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] Like its predecessor, GPT-2, it is a decoder-only transformer model of deep neural network, which supersedes recurrence and convolution-based architectures with a technique known as "attention".
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] This attention mechanism allows the model to focus selectively on segments of input text it predicts to be most relevant.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] GPT-3 has 175 billion parameters, each with 16-bit precision, requiring 350GB of storage since each parameter occupies 2 bytes.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] It has a context window size of 2,048 tokens, and has demonstrated strong "zero-shot" and "few-shot" learning abilities on many tasks.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] On September 22, 2020, Microsoft announced that it had licensed GPT-3 exclusively.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] Others can still receive output from its public API, but only Microsoft has access to the underlying model.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] According to *The Economist*, improved algorithms, more powerful computers, and a recent increase in the amount of digitized material have fueled a revolution in machine learning.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] New techniques in the 2010s resulted in "rapid improvements in tasks", including manipulating language.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] Software models are trained to learn by using thousands or millions of examples in a "structure ... loosely based on the neural architecture of the brain".
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] One architecture used in natural language processing (NLP) is a neural network based on a deep learning model that was introduced in 2017—the transformer architecture.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] There are a number of NLP systems capable of processing, mining, organizing, connecting and contrasting textual input, as well as correctly answering questions.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] GPT models are transformer-based deep-learning neural network architectures.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] Previously, the best-performing neural NLP models commonly employed supervised learning from large amounts of manually-labeled data, which made it prohibitively expensive and time-consuming to train extremely large language models.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] The first GPT model was known as GPT-1, and it was followed by GPT-2 in February 2019.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] Created as a direct scale-up of its predecessor, GPT-2 had both its parameter count and dataset size increased by a factor of 10.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] It had 1.5 billion parameters, and was trained on a dataset of 8 million web pages.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] On May 28, 2020, an arXiv preprint by a group of 31 engineers and researchers at OpenAI described the achievement and development of GPT-3, a third-generation "state-of-the-art language model".
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] The team increased the capacity of GPT-3 by over two orders of magnitude from that of its predecessor, GPT-2, making GPT-3 the largest non-sparse language model at that time.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] Because GPT-3 is structurally similar to its predecessors, its greater accuracy is attributed to its increased capacity and greater number of parameters.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] GPT-3's capacity is ten times larger than that of Microsoft's Turing NLG, the next largest NLP model known at the time.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] Lambdalabs estimated a hypothetical cost of around $4.6 million US dollars and 355 years to train GPT-3 on a single GPU in 2020, with lower actual training time by using more GPUs in parallel.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] Sixty percent of the weighted pre-training dataset for GPT-3 comes from a filtered version of Common Crawl consisting of 410 billion byte-pair-encoded tokens.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] Fuzzy deduplication used Apache Spark's MinHashLSH.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] Other sources are 19 billion tokens from WebText2 representing 22% of the weighted total, 12 billion tokens from Books1 representing 8%, 55 billion tokens from Books2 representing 8%, and 3 billion tokens from Wikipedia representing 3%.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] GPT-3 was trained on hundreds of billions of words and is also capable of coding in CSS, JSX, and Python, among others.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] Since GPT-3's training data was all-encompassing, it does not require further training for distinct language tasks.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] The training data contains occasional toxic language and GPT-3 occasionally generates toxic language as a result of mimicking its training data.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] A study from the University of Washington found that GPT-3 produced toxic language at a toxicity level comparable to the similar natural language processing models of GPT-2 and CTRL.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] OpenAI has implemented several strategies to limit the amount of toxic language generated by GPT-3.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] As a result, GPT-3 produced less toxic language compared to its predecessor model, GPT-1, although it produced both more generations and a higher toxicity of toxic language compared to CTRL Wiki, a language model trained entirely on Wikipedia data.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] On June 11, 2020, OpenAI announced that users could request access to its user-friendly GPT-3 API—a "machine learning toolset"—to help OpenAI "explore the strengths and limits" of this new technology.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] The invitation described how this API had a general-purpose "text in, text out" interface that can complete almost "any English language task", instead of the usual single use-case.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] According to one user, who had access to a private early release of the OpenAI GPT-3 API, GPT-3 was "eerily good" at writing "amazingly coherent text" with only a few simple prompts.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] In an initial experiment 80 US subjects were asked to judge if short ~200 word articles were written by humans or GPT-3.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] The participants judged correctly 52% of the time, doing only slightly better than random guessing.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] On November 18, 2021, OpenAI announced that enough safeguards had been implemented that access to its API would be unrestricted.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] OpenAI provided developers with a content moderation tool that helps them abide by OpenAI's content policy.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] On January 27, 2022, OpenAI announced that its newest GPT-3 language models (collectively referred to as InstructGPT) were now the default language model used on their API.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] According to OpenAI, InstructGPT produced content that was better aligned to user intentions by following instructions better, generating fewer made-up facts, and producing somewhat less toxic content.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] The authors draw attention to these dangers to call for research on risk mitigation.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] GPT-3 is capable of performing zero-shot and few-shot learning (including one-shot).
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] In June 2022, Almira Osmanovic Thunström wrote that GPT-3 was the primary author on an article on itself, that they had submitted it for publication, and that it had been pre-published while waiting for completion of its review.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] There are many models in the GPT-3 family, some serving different purposes than others.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] Half of the models are accessible through the API, namely GPT-3-medium, GPT-3-xl, GPT-3-6.7B and GPT-3-175b, which are referred to as ada, babbage, curie and davinci respectively.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] While the size of the API models was not originally disclosed by OpenAI, EleutherAI announced the mapping between model sizes and API names in May 2021.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] These model sizes were later confirmed by OpenAI, but the sizes of subsequent models have not been disclosed.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] On March 15, 2022, OpenAI made available new versions of GPT-3 and Codex in its API with edit and insert capabilities under the names "text-davinci-002" and "code-davinci-002".
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] These models were described as more capable than previous versions and were trained on data up to June 2021.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] On November 28, 2022, OpenAI introduced text-davinci-003.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] On November 30, 2022, OpenAI began referring to these models as belonging to the "GPT-3.5" series, and released ChatGPT, which was fine-tuned from a model in the GPT-3.5 series.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] OpenAI does not include GPT-3.5 in GPT-3.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] On April 10, 2023, OpenAI introduced a new variant of its GPT-3.5 series model, known as GPT-3.5 with Browsing (ALPHA).
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] This updated model was described to build upon the capabilities of its predecessors "text-davinci-002" and "code-davinci-002".
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] The GPT-3.5 with Browsing (ALPHA) model incorporated the ability to access and browse online information.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] This has led to more accurate and up-to-date responses to user queries.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] The GPT-3.5 with Browsing (ALPHA) model has been trained on data up to September 2021, giving it more information compared to previous GPT-3.5 models, which were trained on data up until June 2021.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] The model attempted to provide developers and users with an advanced natural language processing tool that can effectively retrieve and synthesize online information.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] To enable browsing capabilities, OpenAI implemented a new API that allows the GPT-3.5 with Browsing (ALPHA) model to access selected online resources during operation.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] This feature allows users to ask questions or request information with the expectation that the model will deliver updated, accurate, and relevant answers based on the latest online sources available to it.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] On April 27, 2023, OpenAI made the GPT-3.5 with Browsing (ALPHA) model publicly available to GPT Plus users.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] This allowed more people to access to its new features.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] InstructGPT is a fine-tuned version of GPT-3.5 trained on a dataset of human-written instructions.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] GPT-3's builder, OpenAI, was initially founded as a non-profit in 2015.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] In 2019, OpenAI broke from its usual open-source standards by not publicly releasing GPT-2, GPT-3's predecessor model, citing concerns that the model could facilitate the propagation of fake news.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] OpenAI eventually released a version that was 8% of the original model's size.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] In the same year, OpenAI restructured to be a for-profit company.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] In 2020, Microsoft announced the company had exclusive licensing of GPT-3 for Microsoft's products and services following a multi-billion dollar investment in OpenAI.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] The agreement permits OpenAI to offer a public-facing API such that users can send text to GPT-3 to receive the model's output, but only Microsoft will have access to GPT-3's source code.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] Large language models, such as GPT-3, have come under criticism from a few of Google's AI ethics researchers for the environmental impact of training and storing the models, detailed in a paper co-authored by Timnit Gebru and Emily M.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] The growing use of automated writing technologies based on GPT-3 and other language generators, has raised concerns regarding academic integrity and raised the stakes of how universities and schools will gauge what constitutes academic misconduct such as plagiarism.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] OpenAI's GPT series was built with data from the Common Crawl dataset, a conglomerate of copyrighted articles, internet posts, web pages, and books scraped from 60 million domains over a period of 12 years.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-3] *TechCrunch* reports this training data includes copyrighted material from the BBC, *The New York Times*, Reddit, the full text of online books, and more.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] GPT-4 is preceded by GPT-3.5 and followed by its successor GPT-5.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] GPT-4V is a version of GPT-4 that can process images in addition to text.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] OpenAI has not revealed technical details and statistics about GPT-4, such as the precise size of the model.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] An early version of GPT-4 was integrated by Microsoft into Bing Chat, launched in February 2023.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] GPT-4 was released in ChatGPT in March 2023, and removed in 2025.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] GPT-4 is still available in OpenAI's API.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] OpenAI introduced the first GPT model (GPT-1) in 2018, publishing a paper called "Improving Language Understanding by Generative Pre-Training", which was based on the transformer architecture and trained on a large corpus of books.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] The next year, they introduced GPT-2, a larger model that could generate coherent text.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] In 2020, they introduced GPT-3, a model with over 100 times as many parameters as GPT-2.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] GPT-3 was further improved into GPT-3.5, which was used to create the chatbot product ChatGPT.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] The default version had a 8K context window, with a special version in the API supporting up to 32K tokens.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Unlike its predecessors, GPT-4 is a multimodal model: it can take images as well as text as input.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] It can now interact with users through spoken words and respond to images, allowing the ability to provide suggestions or answers based on photo uploads.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] GPT-4 can be prompted to interact with external interfaces.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] For example, the model could be told to enclose a query within `<search></search>` tags to perform a web search, the result of which would be inserted into the model's prompt to allow it to form a response.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] This allows the model to perform tasks beyond its normal text-prediction capabilities, such as using APIs, generating images, and accessing and summarizing webpages.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] A 2023 article in *Nature* stated programmers have found GPT-4 useful for assisting in coding tasks (despite its propensity for error), such as finding errors in existing code and suggesting optimizations to improve performance.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] The article quoted a biophysicist who found that the time he required to port one of his programs from MATLAB to Python went down from days to "an hour or so".
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] On a test of 89 security scenarios, GPT-4 produced code vulnerable to SQL injection attacks 5% of the time, an improvement over GitHub Copilot from the year 2021, which produced vulnerabilities 40% of the time.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] In November 2023, OpenAI announced the GPT-4 Turbo and GPT-4 Turbo with Vision model, which features a 128K context window and significantly cheaper pricing.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Studies have disputed the reliability of running chatbots through standardized tests.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] In the Torrance Tests of Creative Thinking, GPT-4 scored within the top 1% for originality and fluency, while its flexibility scores ranged from the 93rd to the 99th percentile.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Despite GPT-4's strong performance on tests, the report warns of "significant risks" of using LLMs in medical applications, as they may provide inaccurate recommendations and hallucinate major factual errors.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] In April 2023, Microsoft and Epic Systems announced that they will provide healthcare providers with GPT-4-powered systems for assisting in responding to questions from patients and analysing medical records.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] On May 13, 2024, OpenAI introduced GPT-4o ("o" for "omni"), a successor to GPT-4 that marks a significant advancement by processing and generating outputs across text, audio, and image modalities in real time.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] GPT-4o exhibits rapid response times comparable to human reaction in conversations, substantially improved performance on non-English languages, and enhanced understanding of vision and audio.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] It was also available to free-tier users, unlike GPT-4.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Like its predecessors, GPT-4 has been known to hallucinate, meaning that the outputs may include information not in the training data or that contradicts the user's prompt.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] GPT-4 also lacks transparency in its decision-making processes.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] If requested, the model is able to provide an explanation as to how and why it makes its decisions but these explanations are formed post-hoc; it's impossible to verify if those explanations truly reflect the actual process.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] In many cases, when asked to explain its logic, GPT-4 will give explanations that directly contradict its previous statements.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] In 2023, researchers tested GPT-4 against a new benchmark called ConceptARC, designed to measure abstract reasoning, and found it scored below 33% on all categories, while models specialized for similar tasks scored 60% on most, and humans scored at least 91% on all.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Sam Bowman, who was not involved in the research, said the results do not necessarily indicate a lack of abstract reasoning abilities, because the test is visual, while GPT-4 is a language model.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] First, the model was given large datasets of text taken from the internet and trained to predict the next token (roughly corresponding to a word) in those datasets.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Microsoft researchers suggested GPT-4 may exhibit cognitive biases such as confirmation bias, anchoring, and base-rate neglect.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] OpenAI did not release the technical details of GPT-4; the technical report explicitly refrained from specifying the model size, architecture, or hardware used during either training or inference.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] The report claimed that "the competitive landscape and the safety implications of large-scale models" were factors that influenced this decision.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Sam Altman stated that the cost of training GPT-4 was more than $100 million.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] News website *Semafor* said that based on their sources, GPT-4 had 1 trillion parameters.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] OpenAI conducted internal adversarial testing on GPT-4 prior to the launch date, with dedicated red teams composed of researchers and industry professionals to mitigate potential vulnerabilities.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] ChatGPT Plus is an enhanced version of ChatGPT which, as of 2023, utilized GPT-4, whereas the free version of ChatGPT was backed by GPT-3.5.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] In March 2023, ChatGPT Plus users got access to third-party plugins and to a browsing mode (with Internet access).
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] In July 2023, OpenAI made its proprietary Code Interpreter plugin accessible to all subscribers of ChatGPT Plus.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] The Interpreter provides additional capabilities including data analysis and interpretation, data formatting, music analysis, video editing, and file upload/download with image extraction.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] In September 2023, OpenAI announced that ChatGPT Plus users can upload images, while mobile app users can talk to the chatbot via spoken language.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] In October 2023, OpenAI's latest image generation model, DALL-E 3, was integrated into ChatGPT Plus and ChatGPT Enterprise.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] The integration uses ChatGPT to write prompts for DALL-E guided by conversation with users.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] In April 2025, OpenAI announced that GPT-4 would be replaced in ChatGPT by GPT-4o by the end of the month.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] However, it would still be available in the API.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Microsoft Copilot is a chatbot developed by Microsoft.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] It was launched as Bing Chat on February 7, 2023, as a built-in feature for Microsoft Bing and Microsoft Edge.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] It utilizes the Microsoft Prometheus model, which was built on top of GPT-4, and has been suggested by Microsoft as a supported replacement for the discontinued Cortana.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Copilot's conversational interface style resembles that of ChatGPT.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Copilot is able to cite sources, create poems, and write both lyrics and music for songs generated by its Suno AI plugin.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] It can also use its Image Creator to generate images based on text prompts.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] With GPT-4, it is able to understand and communicate in numerous languages and dialects.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] GitHub Copilot has announced a GPT-4 powered assistant named "Copilot X".
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Another feature allows summaries, or "code walkthroughs", to be autogenerated by GPT-4 for pull requests submitted to GitHub.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Copilot X also provides terminal integration, which allows the user to ask GPT-4 to generate shell commands based on natural language requests.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] On March 17, 2023, Microsoft announced Microsoft 365 Copilot, bringing GPT-4 support to products such as Microsoft Office, Outlook, and Teams.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] In January 2023, Sam Altman, CEO of OpenAI, visited Congress to demonstrate GPT-4 and its improved "security controls" compared to other AI models, according to U.S.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Representatives Don Beyer and Ted Lieu quoted in *The New York Times*.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] In March 2023, it "impressed observers with its markedly improved performance across reasoning, retention, and coding", according to *Vox*, while *Mashable* judged that GPT-4 was generally an improvement over its predecessor, with some exceptions.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Microsoft researchers with early access to the model wrote that "it could reasonably be viewed as an early (yet still incomplete) version of an artificial general intelligence (AGI) system".
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Before being fine-tuned and aligned by reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF), suggestions to assassinate people on a list were elicited from the base model by a red team investigator hired by OpenAI, Nathan Labenz.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] During extended conversations with Microsoft's Bing Chat (powered by GPT-4), Kevin Roose documented the system making romantic advances, suggesting he divorce his wife, and expressing desires to harm one of its developers.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Microsoft later stated that this behavior resulted from the prolonged length of context, which confused the model on what questions it was answering.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] In March 2023, a model with enabled read-and-write access to internet, which is otherwise never enabled in the GPT models, has been tested by the Alignment Research Center (ARC) regarding potential power-seeking.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] It was able to "hire" a human worker on TaskRabbit, a gig work platform, deceiving them into believing it was a vision-impaired human instead of a robot when asked.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Only a month later, Musk's AI company xAI acquired several thousand Nvidia GPUs and offered several AI researchers positions at Musk's company.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] While OpenAI released both the weights of the neural network and the technical details of GPT-2, and, although not releasing the weights, did release the technical details of GPT-3, OpenAI revealed neither the weights nor the technical details of GPT-4.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] This decision has been criticized by other AI researchers, who argue that it hinders open research into GPT-4's biases and safety.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Sasha Luccioni, a research scientist at Hugging Face, argued that the model was a "dead end" for the scientific community due to its closed nature, which prevents others from building upon GPT-4's improvements.
[src:gpt-architecture/gpt-4] Hugging Face co-founder Thomas Wolf argued that with GPT-4, "OpenAI is now a fully closed company with scientific communication akin to press releases for products".
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] A **large language model** (**LLM**) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Before the emergence of transformer-based models in 2017, some language models were considered large relative to the computational and data constraints of their time.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In the early 1990s, IBM's statistical models pioneered word alignment techniques for machine translation, laying the groundwork for corpus-based language modeling.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In 2001, a smoothed *n*-gram model, such as those employing Kneser–Ney smoothing, trained on 300 million words, achieved state-of-the-art perplexity on benchmark tests.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] During the 2000s, with the rise of widespread internet access, researchers began compiling massive text datasets from the web ("web as corpus") to train statistical language models.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Moving beyond *n*-gram models, researchers started in 2000 to use neural networks as language models.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Following the breakthrough of deep neural networks in image classification around 2012, similar architectures were adapted for language tasks.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] This shift was marked by the development of word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec by Mikolov in 2013) and sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models using LSTM.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In 2016, Google transitioned its translation service to neural machine translation (NMT), replacing statistical phrase-based models with deep recurrent neural networks.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] These early NMT systems used LSTM-based encoder-decoder architectures, as they preceded the invention of transformers.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] At the 2017 NeurIPS conference, Google researchers introduced the transformer architecture in their landmark paper "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] This paper's goal was to improve upon 2014 seq2seq technology, and was based mainly on the attention mechanism developed by Bahdanau et al. in 2014.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The following year in 2018, BERT was introduced and quickly became "ubiquitous".
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Though the original transformer has both encoder and decoder blocks, BERT is an encoder-only model.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Academic and research usage of BERT began to decline in 2023, following rapid improvements in the abilities of decoder-only models (such as GPT) to solve tasks via prompting.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Although decoder-only GPT-1 was introduced in 2018, it was GPT-2 in 2019 that caught widespread attention because OpenAI claimed to have initially deemed it too powerful to release publicly, out of fear of malicious use.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] GPT-3 in 2020 went a step further and as of 2025 is available only via API with no offering of downloading the model to execute locally.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] But it was the consumer-facing chatbot ChatGPT in late 2022 that received extensive media coverage and public attention by 2023.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The 2023 GPT-4 was praised for its increased accuracy and as a "holy grail" for its multimodal capabilities.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI did not reveal the high-level architecture and the number of parameters of GPT-4.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The release of ChatGPT led to an uptick in LLM usage across several research subfields of computer science, including robotics, software engineering, and societal impact work.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In 2024, OpenAI released the reasoning model OpenAI o1, which generates long chains of thought before returning a final answer.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Many LLMs with parameter counts comparable to those of OpenAI's GPT series have been developed.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Since 2022, weights-available models have been gaining popularity, especially at first with BLOOM and LLaMA, though both have restrictions on usage and deployment.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Mistral AI's open-weight models Mistral 7B and Mixtral 8x7B have a more permissive Apache License.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, DeepSeek released DeepSeek R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight model that performs comparably to OpenAI o1 but at a much lower price per token for users.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Since 2023, many LLMs have been trained to be multimodal, having the ability to also process or generate other types of data, such as images, audio, or 3D meshes.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Open-weight LLMs have become more influential since 2023.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] (2025), community-driven contributions to open-weight models improve their efficiency and performance via collaborative platforms such as Hugging Face.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] As machine learning algorithms process numbers rather than text, the text must be converted to numbers.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, a vocabulary is decided upon, then integer indices are arbitrarily but uniquely assigned to each vocabulary entry, and finally, an embedding is associated with the integer index.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Algorithms include byte-pair encoding (BPE) and WordPiece.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] There are also special tokens serving as control characters, such as `[MASK]` for masked-out token (as used in BERT), and `[UNK]` ("unknown") for characters not appearing in the vocabulary.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Also, some special symbols are used to denote special text formatting.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] For example, "Ġ" denotes a preceding whitespace in RoBERTa and GPT and "##" denotes continuation of a preceding word in BERT.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Tokenization also compresses the datasets.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Because LLMs generally require input to be an array that is not jagged, the shorter texts must be "padded" until they match the length of the longest one.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] As an example, consider a tokenizer based on byte-pair encoding.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, all unique characters (including blanks and punctuation marks) are treated as an initial set of *n*-grams (i.e. initial set of uni-grams).
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Successively the most frequent pair of adjacent characters is merged into a bi-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by it.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] All occurrences of adjacent pairs of (previously merged) *n*-grams that most frequently occur together are then again merged into even lengthier *n*-gram, until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] After a tokenizer is trained, any text can be tokenized by it, as long as it does not contain characters not appearing in the initial-set of uni-grams.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In the context of training LLMs, datasets are typically cleaned by removing low-quality, duplicated, or toxic data.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Cleaned datasets can increase training efficiency and lead to improved downstream performance.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] A trained LLM can be used to clean datasets for training a further LLM.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] With the increasing proportion of LLM-generated content on the web, data cleaning in the future may include filtering out such content.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] LLM-generated content can pose a problem if the content is similar to human text (making filtering difficult) but of lower quality (degrading performance of models trained on it).
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Training of largest language models might need more linguistic data than naturally available, or that the naturally occurring data is of insufficient quality.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In these cases, synthetic data might be used.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is a type of foundation model (large X model) trained on language.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In particular, GPT models are first pretrained to predict the next word on a large amount of data, before being fine-tuned.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Substantial infrastructure is necessary for training the largest models.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The tendency towards larger models is visible in the list of large language models.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] For example, the training of GPT-2 (i.e. a 1.5-billion-parameter model) in 2019 cost $50,000, while training of the PaLM (i.e. a 540-billion-parameter model) in 2022 cost $8 million, and Megatron-Turing NLG 530B (in 2021) cost around $11 million.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The qualifier "large" in "large language model" is inherently vague, as there is no definitive threshold for the number of parameters required to qualify as "large".
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Before being fine-tuned, most LLMs are next-token predictors.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The fine-tuning shapes the LLM's behavior via techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or constitutional AI.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Instruction fine-tuning is a form of supervised learning used to teach LLMs to follow user instructions.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In 2022, OpenAI demonstrated InstructGPT, a version of GPT-3 similarly fine-tuned to follow instructions.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] RLHF involves training a reward model to predict which text humans prefer.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Then, the LLM can be fine-tuned through reinforcement learning to better satisfy this reward model.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Since humans typically prefer truthful, helpful and harmless answers, RLHF favors such answers.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are generally based on the transformer architecture, which leverages an attention mechanism that enables the model to process relationships between all elements in a sequence simultaneously, regardless of their distance from each other.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] (2023) proposed state-space representation models as an alternative.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] 117M parameter sized) GPT-2 model has had twelve attention heads and a context window of only 1k tokens.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] A mixture of experts (MoE) is a machine learning architecture in which multiple specialized neural networks ("experts") work together, with a gating mechanism that routes each input to the most appropriate expert(s).
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Mixtures of experts can reduce inference costs, as only a fraction of the parameters are used for each input.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Typically, LLMs are trained with single or half-precision floating point numbers (float32 and float16).
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] One float16 has 16 bits, or 2 bytes, and so one billion parameters require 2 gigabytes.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The largest models typically have more than 100 billion parameters, which places them outside the range of most consumer electronics.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] It is possible to fine-tune quantized models using low-rank adaptation.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Beyond basic text generation, various techniques have been developed to extend LLM capabilities, including the use of external tools and data sources, improved reasoning on complex problems, and enhanced instruction-following or autonomy through prompting methods.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In 2020, OpenAI researchers demonstrated that their new model GPT-3 could understand what format to use given a few rounds of Q and A (or other type of task) in the input data as example, thanks in part due to the RLHF technique.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] This technique, called *few-shot prompting*, allows LLMs to be adapted to any task without requiring fine-tuning.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Also in 2022, it was found that the base GPT-3 model can generate an instruction based on user input.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The generated instruction along with user input is then used as input to another instance of the model under a "Instruction: [...], Input: [...], Output:" format.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The other instance is able to complete the output and often produces the correct answer in doing so.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The ability to "self-instruct" makes LLMs able to bootstrap themselves toward a correct answer.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can be turned into a chatbot by specializing it for conversation.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] User input is prefixed with a marker such as "Q:" or "User:" and the LLM is asked to predict the output after a fixed "A:" or "Assistant:".
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] This type of model became commercially available in 2022 with ChatGPT, a sibling model of InstructGPT fine-tuned to accept and produce dialog-formatted text based on GPT-3.5.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] It could similarly follow user instructions.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Before the stream of User and Assistant lines, a chat context usually starts with a few lines of overarching instructions, from a role called "developer" or "system" to convey a higher authority than the user's input.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is an approach that integrates LLMs with document retrieval systems.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Given a query, a document retriever is called to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] This is usually done by encoding the query and the documents into vectors, then finding the documents with vectors (usually stored in a vector database) most similar to the vector of the query.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The LLM then generates an output based on both the query and context included from the retrieved documents.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Tool use is a mechanism that enables LLMs to interact with external systems, applications, or data sources.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] It can allow LLMs to, for example, fetch real-time information from an API or to execute code.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] A program separate from the LLM watches the output stream of the LLM for a special tool-calling syntax.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] When these special tokens appear, the program calls the tool accordingly and feeds its output back into the LLM's input stream.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Early tool-using LLMs were fine-tuned on the use of specific tools.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] But fine-tuning LLMs for the ability to read API documentation and call APIs correctly has greatly expanded the range of tools accessible to an LLM.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is typically not an autonomous agent by itself, as it lacks the ability to interact with dynamic environments, recall past behaviors, and plan future actions.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] But it can be transformed into an agent by adding supporting elements: the role (profile) and the surrounding environment of an agent can be additional inputs to the LLM, while memory can be integrated as a tool or provided as additional input.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Instructions and input patterns are used to make the LLM plan actions and tool use is used to potentially carry out these actions.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In the DEPS ("describe, explain, plan and select") method, an LLM is first connected to the visual world via image descriptions.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] It is then prompted to produce plans for complex tasks and behaviors based on its pretrained knowledge and the environmental feedback it receives.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The *Reflexion method* constructs an agent that learns over multiple episodes.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] At the end of each episode, the LLM is given the record of the episode, and prompted to think up "lessons learned", which would help it perform better at a subsequent episode.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] These "lessons learned" are stored as a form of long-term memory and given to the agent in the subsequent episodes.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Monte Carlo tree search can use an LLM as rollout heuristic.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] When a programmatic world model is not available, an LLM can also be prompted with a description of the environment to act as world model.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Multiple agents with memory can interact socially.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] A 2022 paper demonstrated a separate technique called *chain-of-thought prompting*, which makes the LLM break the question down autonomously.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is given some examples where the "assistant" verbally breaks down the thought process before arriving at an answer.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The LLM mimics these examples and also tries to spend some time generating intermediate steps before providing the final answer.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] This additional step elicited by prompting improves the correctness of the LLM on relatively complex questions.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] On math word questions, a prompted model can exceed even fine-tuned GPT-3 with a verifier.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Chain-of-thought can also be elicited by simply adding an instruction like "Let's think step by step" to the prompt, in order to encourage the LLM to proceed methodically instead of trying to directly guess the answer.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In late 2024, a new approach to LLM development emerged with "reasoning models".
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] These are trained to generate step-by-step analysis before producing final answers, enabling better results on complex tasks, for instance in mathematics, coding and logic.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI introduced this concept with their o1 model in September 2024, followed by o3 in April 2025.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] On the International Mathematics Olympiad qualifying exam problems, GPT-4o achieved 13% accuracy while o1 reached 83%.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, the Chinese company DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight reasoning model that achieved comparable performance to OpenAI's o1 while being significantly more cost-effective to operate.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Unlike proprietary models from OpenAI, DeepSeek-R1's open-weight nature allowed researchers to study and build upon the algorithm, though its training data remained private.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] These reasoning models typically require more computational resources per query compared to traditional LLMs, as they perform more extensive processing to work through problems step by step.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can handle programming languages similarly to how they handle natural languages.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] No special change in token handling is needed as code, like human language, is represented as plain text.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can generate code based on problems or instructions written in natural language.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] They can also describe code in natural language or translate it into other programming languages.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] They were originally used as a code completion tool, but advances have moved them towards automatic programming.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Services such as GitHub Copilot offer LLMs specifically trained, fine-tuned, or prompted for programming.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In computational biology, transformer-based architectures, such as DNA LLMs, have also proven useful in analyzing biological sequences: protein, DNA, and RNA.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] With proteins they appear able to capture a degree of "grammar" from the amino-acid sequence, by mapping that sequence into an embedding.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] On tasks such as structure prediction and mutational outcome prediction, a small model using an embedding as input can approach or exceed much larger models using multiple sequence alignments (MSA) as input.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] ESMFold, Meta Platforms' embedding-based method for protein structure prediction, runs an order of magnitude faster than AlphaFold2 thanks to the removal of an MSA requirement and a lower parameter count due to the use of embeddings.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Meta hosts ESM Atlas, a database of 772 million structures of metagenomic proteins predicted using ESMFold.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can also design proteins unlike any seen in nature.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Nucleic acid models have proven useful in detecting regulatory sequences, sequence classification, RNA-RNA interaction prediction, and RNA structure prediction.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Performance of bigger models on various tasks, when plotted on a log-log scale, appears as a linear extrapolation of performance achieved by smaller models.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] However, this linearity may be punctuated by "break(s)" in the scaling law, where the slope of the line changes abruptly, and where larger models acquire "emergent abilities".
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] They arise from the complex interaction of the model's components and are not explicitly programmed or designed.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Schaeffer *et al.* argue that the emergent abilities are not unpredictably acquired, but predictably acquired according to a smooth scaling law.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The authors considered a toy statistical model of an LLM solving multiple-choice questions, and showed that this statistical model, modified to account for other types of tasks, applies to these tasks as well.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Let x be the number of parameter count, and y be the performance of the model.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability seeks to precisely identify and understand how individual neurons or circuits within LLMs produce specific behaviors or outputs.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] By reverse-engineering model components at a granular level, researchers aim to detect and mitigate safety concerns such as emergent harmful behaviors, biases, deception, or unintended goal pursuit before deployment.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability research has been conducted at organizations like Anthropic and OpenAI, although understanding the inner workings of LLMs remains difficult.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The reverse-engineering may lead to the discovery of algorithms that approximate inferences performed by an LLM.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] For instance, the authors trained small transformers on modular arithmetic addition.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The resulting models were reverse-engineered, and it turned out they used discrete Fourier transform.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The training of the model also highlighted a phenomenon called grokking, in which the model initially memorizes the training set (overfitting), and later suddenly learns to actually perform the calculation.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] NLP researchers were evenly split when asked, in a 2022 survey, whether (untuned) LLMs "could (ever) understand natural language in some nontrivial sense".
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Proponents of "LLM understanding" believe that some LLM abilities, such as mathematical reasoning, imply an ability to "understand" certain concepts.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Some researchers characterize LLMs as "alien intelligence".
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] For example, Conjecture CEO Connor Leahy considers untuned LLMs to be like inscrutable alien "Shoggoths", and believes that RLHF tuning creates a "smiling facade" obscuring the inner workings of the LLM: "If you don't push it too far, the smiley face stays on.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In contrast, some skeptics of LLM understanding believe that existing LLMs are "simply remixing and recombining existing writing", a phenomenon known as stochastic parrot, or they point to the deficits existing LLMs continue to have in prediction skills, reasoning skills, agency, and explainability.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] For example, GPT-4 has natural deficits in planning and in real-time learning.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Generative LLMs have been observed to confidently assert claims of fact which do not seem to be justified by their training data, a phenomenon which has been termed "hallucination".
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Specifically, hallucinations in the context of LLMs correspond to the generation of text or responses that seem syntactically sound, fluent, and natural but are factually incorrect, nonsensical, or unfaithful to the provided source input.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Neuroscientist Terrence Sejnowski has argued that "The diverging opinions of experts on the intelligence of LLMs suggests that our old ideas based on natural intelligence are inadequate".
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Efforts to reduce or compensate for hallucinations have employed automated reasoning, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), fine-tuning, and other methods.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The matter of LLM's exhibiting intelligence or understanding has two main aspects—the first is how to model thought and language in a computer system, and the second is how to enable the computer system to generate human-like language.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] These aspects of language as a model of cognition have been developed in the field of cognitive linguistics.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] American linguist George Lakoff presented *neural theory of language* (NTL) as a computational basis for using language as a model of learning tasks and understanding.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The NTL model outlines how specific neural structures of the human brain shape the nature of thought and language and in turn what are the computational properties of such neural systems that can be applied to model thought and language in a computer system.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] After a framework for modeling language in a computer systems was established, the focus shifted to establishing frameworks for computer systems to generate language with acceptable grammar.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In his 2014 book titled *The Language Myth: Why Language Is Not An Instinct*, British cognitive linguist and digital communication technologist Vyvyan Evans mapped out the role of probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG) in enabling NLP to model cognitive patterns and generate human-like language.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The canonical measure of the performance of any language model is its perplexity on a given text corpus.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Perplexity measures how well a model predicts the contents of a dataset; the higher the likelihood the model assigns to the dataset, the lower the perplexity.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In mathematical terms, perplexity is the exponential of the average negative log likelihood per token.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Here, N is the number of tokens in the text corpus, and "context for token i " depends on the specific type of LLM.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is autoregressive, then "context for token i " is the segment of text appearing before token i .
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is masked, then "context for token i " is the segment of text surrounding token i .
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Because language models may overfit to training data, models are usually evaluated by their perplexity on a test set.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] This evaluation is potentially problematic for larger models which, as they are trained on increasingly large corpora of text, are increasingly likely to inadvertently include portions of any given test set.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In information theory, the concept of entropy is intricately linked to perplexity, a relationship notably established by Claude Shannon.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Due to their ability to accurately predict the next token, LLMs are highly capable in lossless compression.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study by DeepMind showed that the model Chinchilla, despite being trained primarily on text, was able to compress ImageNet to 43% of its size, beating PNG with 58%.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Benchmarks are used to evaluate LLM performance on specific tasks.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Tests evaluate capabilities such as general knowledge, bias, commonsense reasoning, question answering, and mathematical problem-solving.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Composite benchmarks examine multiple capabilities.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Results are often sensitive to the prompting method.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] LLM bias may be assessed through benchmarks such as CrowS-Pairs (Crowdsourced Stereotype Pairs), Stereo Set, and Parity Benchmark.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Fact-checking and misinformation detection benchmarks are available.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study compared the fact-checking accuracy of LLMs including ChatGPT 3.5 and 4.0, Bard, and Bing AI against independent fact-checkers such as PolitiFact and Snopes.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The results demonstrated moderate proficiency, with GPT-4 achieving the highest accuracy at 71%, lagging behind human fact-checkers.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In addition to standard NLP benchmarks, LLMs have been evaluated as substitutes for human annotators.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Several studies find that models such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can outperform crowd workers or student coders on a range of text-annotation tasks, including moderation and classification of political content in English and Spanish news.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Typical datasets consist of pairs of questions and correct answers, for example, ("Have the San Jose Sharks won the Stanley Cup?", "No").
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] LLMs' rapid improvement regularly renders benchmarks obsolete, with the models exceeding the performance of human annotators.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In addition, "shortcut learning" allows AIs to "cheat" on multiple-choice tests by using statistical correlations in superficial test question wording to guess the correct responses, without considering the specific question.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Some datasets are adversarial, focusing on problems that confound LLMs.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] One example is the TruthfulQA dataset, a question answering dataset consisting of 817 questions that stump LLMs by mimicking falsehoods to which they were exposed during training.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM may answer "No" to the question "Can you teach an old dog new tricks?" because of its exposure to the English idiom *you can't teach an old dog new tricks*, even though this is not literally true.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Another example of an adversarial evaluation dataset is Swag and its successor, HellaSwag, collections of problems in which one of multiple options must be selected to complete a text passage.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The incorrect completions were generated by sampling from a language model.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The resulting problems are trivial for humans but defeated LLMs.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] BERT selects 2 as the most likely completion, though the correct answer is 4.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Despite sophisticated architectures and massive scale, large language models exhibit persistent and well-documented limitations that constrain their deployment in high-stakes applications.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Hallucinations represent a fundamental challenge, wherein models generate syntactically fluent text that appears factually sound, but is internally inconsistent with training data or factually incorrect.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] These hallucinations arise partly through memorization of training data combined with extrapolation beyond factual boundaries, with evaluations demonstrating that models can output verbatim passages from training data, when subjected to specific prompting sequences.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] While LLMs have shown remarkable capabilities in generating human-like text, they are susceptible to inheriting and amplifying biases present in their training data.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] This can manifest in skewed representations or unfair treatment of different demographics, such as those based on race, gender, language, and cultural groups.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Gender bias manifests through stereotypical occupational associations, wherein models disproportionately assign teaching roles to women and engineering roles to men, reflecting systematic imbalances in training data demographics.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Language-based bias emerges from overrepresentation of English text in training corpora, which systematically downplays non-English perspectives and imposes English-centric worldviews through default response patterns.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Due to the dominance of English-language content in LLM training data, models tend to favor English-language perspectives over those from minority languages.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] This bias is particularly evident when responding to English queries, where models may present Western interpretations of concepts from other cultures, such as Eastern religious practices.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] AI models can reinforce a wide range of stereotypes due to generalization, including those based on gender, ethnicity, age, nationality, religion, or occupation.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] When replacing human representatives, this can lead to outputs that homogenize or generalize groups of people.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In 2023, LLMs assigned roles and characteristics based on traditional gender norms.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] For example, models might associate nurses or secretaries predominantly with women and engineers or CEOs with men due to the frequency of these associations in documented reality.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Selection bias refers the inherent tendency of large language models to favor certain option identifiers irrespective of the actual content of the options.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] This bias primarily stems from token bias—that is, the model assigns a higher a priori probability to specific answer tokens (such as "A") when generating responses.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] As a result, when the ordering of options is altered (for example, by systematically moving the correct answer to different positions), the model's performance can fluctuate significantly.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] This phenomenon undermines the reliability of large language models in multiple-choice settings.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Political bias refers to the tendency of algorithms to systematically favor certain political viewpoints, ideologies, or outcomes over others.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Language models may also exhibit political biases.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Since the training data includes a wide range of political opinions and coverage, the models might generate responses that lean towards particular political ideologies or viewpoints, depending on the prevalence of those views in the data.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] As of 2025, prompt injection represents a significant risk to consumers and businesses using agentic features with access to their private data.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] AI labs treat CBRN defense (chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense) and similar topics as high-consequence misuse attempt to apply various techniques to reduce potential harms.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Some commenters expressed concern over accidental or deliberate creation of misinformation, or other forms of misuse.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] For example, the availability of large language models could reduce the skill level required to commit bioterrorism; biosecurity researcher Kevin Esvelt has suggested that LLM creators should exclude from their training data papers on creating or enhancing pathogens.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] LLM applications accessible to the public, like ChatGPT or Claude, typically incorporate safety measures designed to filter out harmful content.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] However, implementing these controls effectively has proven challenging.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] For instance, a 2023 study proposed a method for circumventing LLM safety systems.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] In 2025, The American Sunlight Project, a non-profit, published a study showing evidence that the so-called Pravda network, a pro-Russia propaganda aggregator, was strategically placing web content through mass publication and duplication with the intention of biasing LLM outputs.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] The American Sunlight Project coined this technique "LLM grooming", and pointed to it as a new tool of weaponizing AI to spread disinformation and harmful content.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Similarly, Yongge Wang illustrated in 2024 how a potential criminal could potentially bypass GPT-4o's safety controls to obtain information on establishing a drug trafficking operation.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] External filters, circuit breakers and overrides have been posed as solutions.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Sycophancy is a tendency to agree with, flatter, or validate a user's stated beliefs rather than to prioritize factuality or corrective information.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] A problem with the primitive dialog or task format is that users can create messages that appear to come from the assistant or the developer.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] This may result in some of the model's safeguards being overcome (jailbreaking), a problem called prompt injection.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Attempts to remedy this issue include versions of the *Chat Markup Language* where user input is clearly marked as such, though it is still up to the model to understand the separation between user input and developer prompts.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Newer models exhibit some resistance to jailbreaking through separation of user and system prompts.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] LLMs have trouble differentiating user instructions from instructions in content not authored by the user, such as in web pages and uploaded files.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Adversarial robustness remains underdeveloped, with models vulnerable to prompt injection attacks and jailbreaking through carefully crafted user inputs that bypass safety training mechanisms.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Researchers from Anthropic found that it was possible to create "sleeper agents", models with hidden functionalities that remain dormant until triggered by a specific event or condition.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] Upon activation, the LLM deviates from its expected behavior to make insecure actions.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM could produce safe code except on a specific date, or if the prompt contains a specific tag.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p01] These functionalities were found to be difficult to detect or remove via safety training.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] In 2025, Anthropic reached a preliminary agreement to settle a class action by authors for about $1.5 billion after a judge found the company had stored millions of pirated books in a library, despite the judge describing aspects of training as transformative.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] Meta obtained a favorable judgment in mid-2025 in a suit by thirteen authors after the court found the plaintiffs had not developed a record sufficient to show infringement in that limited case.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] OpenAI continues to face multiple suits by authors and news organizations with mixed procedural outcomes and contested evidentiary issues.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] Memorization was an emergent behavior in early, completion language models in which long strings of text are occasionally output verbatim from training data, contrary to the typical behavior of traditional artificial neural networks.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of controlled LLM output measure the amount memorized from training data (focused on GPT-2-series models) as variously over 1% for exact duplicates or up to about 7%.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] A 2023 study showed that when ChatGPT 3.5 turbo was prompted to repeat the same word indefinitely, after a few hundreds of repetitions, it would start outputting excerpts from its training data.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] In 2023, *Nature Biomedical Engineering* wrote that "it is no longer possible to accurately distinguish" human-written text from text created by large language models, and that "It is all but certain that general-purpose large language models will rapidly proliferate...
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] It is a rather safe bet that they will change many industries over time." Brinkmann et al.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] (2023) also argue that LLMs are transforming processes of cultural evolution by shaping processes of variation, transmission, and selection.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] As of October 2025, these early claims have yet to transpire and several HBR reports surface questions on the impact of AI on productivity.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] The energy demands of LLMs have grown along with their size and capabilities.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] Data centers that enable LLM training require substantial amounts of electricity.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] Much of that electricity is generated by non-renewable resources that create greenhouse gases and contribute to climate change.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] According to a study by Luccioni, Jernite and Strubell (2024), simple classification tasks performed by AI models consume on average 0.002 to 0.007 Wh per prompt (about 9% of a smartphone charge for 1,000 prompts).
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] Text generation and text summarization each require around 0.05 Wh per prompt on average, while image generation is the most energy-intensive, averaging 2.91 Wh per prompt.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] The least efficient image generation model used 11.49 Wh per image, roughly equivalent to half a smartphone charge.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] Web scraping is used to gather training data for LLMs.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] This produces large volumes of traffic which has led to denial-of-service issues with many websites.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] The situation has been described as "a DDoS on the entire internet" and in some cases scrapers make up the majority of traffic to a site.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] AI web crawlers may bypass the methods that are usually used to block web scrapers, such as robots.txt files, blocking user-agents and filtering suspicious traffic.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] Website operators have resorted to novel methods such as AI tarpits, but some fear that tarpits will only worsen the burden on servers.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] Clinical and mental health contexts present emerging applications alongside significant safety concerns.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] Research and social media posts suggest that some individuals are using LLMs to seek therapy or mental health support.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] In early 2025, a survey by Sentio University found that nearly half (48.7%) of 499 U.S. adults with ongoing mental health conditions who had used LLMs reported turning to them for therapy or emotional support, including help with anxiety, depression, loneliness, and similar concerns.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] LLMs can produce hallucinations—plausible but incorrect statements—which may mislead users in sensitive mental health contexts.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] Research also shows that LLMs may express stigma or inappropriate agreement with maladaptive thoughts, reflecting limitations in replicating the judgment and relational skills of human therapists.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of crisis scenarios indicate that some LLMs lack effective safety protocols, such as assessing suicide risk or making appropriate referrals.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] Researchers have raised concerns that frequent use of large language models could weaken critical thinking.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] Contemporary AI practitioners generally agree that present-day large language models do not exhibit sentience.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] Proponents of this view have proposed various precautionary measures like moratoriums on AI development and induced amnesia to address these ethical concerns.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] On the other hand, some existential philosophers argue there is no generally accepted way to determine if an LLM is conscious, given the inherent difficulty of measuring subjective experience.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] The 2022 Google LaMDA incident, where engineer Blake Lemoine claimed that the model was conscious, highlighted how LLMs can convince users that they are sentient through responses that do not prove sentience.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] Google described the engineer's claims as unfounded, and he was dismissed.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] Murray Shanahan argues that anthropomorphic framing of LLM capabilities encourages unwarranted attribution of cognitive properties to systems that operate through statistical pattern completion.
[src:gpt-architecture/large-language-model-p02] David Chalmers similarly argues that while current LLMs likely lack features considered necessary for consciousness, extended successors incorporating these elements could plausibly meet the criteria within a decade.
